Articles.Content: My son has been playing KSP on our computer for a while.  Starting in recent days KSP will not load. The progress bar at the bottom of the splash screen chugs along, gets to about 50%, and then resets to about 1/3rd and shows "Module Manager" and will not progress any further.  Apologies for not knowing what to do but this is all new to me and I'm just trying to reduce frustration in our house.  Any guidance on what to do, short of uninstalling and reinstalling, would be greatly appreciated.
Although I have VERY little knowledge of modding in a general sense, may I ask what version of Module Manager he might be using? An outdated version may be the issue here.

Let me try to help. Go where KSP is installed ( if using steam C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\steamapps\common\Kerbal Space Program\ ) and get the output_log.txt you hsould find insde the KSPDev_Data on a service like dropbox so we can see what is going on.

As a short term solution : There was an update to ModuleManager yesterday so have a look in the GameData subfodloder of KSP and you should see a ModuleManager.2.6.xx.dll. If the xx is 17 then delete is and replace it with this one https://ksp.sarbian.com/jenkins/job/ModuleManager/104/artifact/ModuleManager.2.6.16.dll

if the version is not the 2.617 then try it : https://ksp.sarbian.com/jenkins/job/ModuleManager/105/artifact/ModuleManager.2.6.17.dll

But I would really like to see that log

Edited January 11, 2016 by sarbian
When MM hangs on startup, i usually delete all the ModuleManager files (configcache/configSHA/Physics/Techtree) except ModuleManager itself, fixes hangs most of the time.

Thanks to everyone for the suggestions.  We deleted the module manager files per micr0wave's suggestion.  Then we just downloaded Module Manager 2.6.17 and are opening KSP.

Unfortunately it did not work.  I am having trouble attaching the output file (need to work on that as a different issue) per sarbian's suggestion. Again I really

The problem is that you have a bunch of mods installed in the wrong directory and ModuleManger is freaking out for some reason. Since it is quite a few mod that are not where they should be I think the easier way would be to delete the content of GameData, let Steam download the missing files again and re install the mods you need properly. Your son saves will be fine since they are in the <KSP>/saves directory
So : 
 - go the KSP directory and delete GameData
 - in Steam right click on KSP on the list, properties, "Local files" tab and press the "Verify integrity" button. It will check the files and download the missing one.
 - to get and install the missing mod easily I suggest you use a mod manager like CKAN. Just get the exe here, put it somewhere and launch it. Select the mods you want in the list and press install. From what I see in the log the mod that were installed are "AoA Tech", "Asteroid Day", "Custom Cluster", "Kerbal Aircraft Expansion", "Near Future Electrical", "Porkalike Rapier" and "Planetary Base"
 
I hope this will work for you.

Hello,

My opinion for what it is worth here - do not use CKAN (until you are more proficient at loading and unloading MODS).

Load up one MOD at a time; use MODS that are important to your play style but understand thier use.

For example load texture mods last after others load.

MODS go in the Gamedata directory.

CKAN is some kind of MOD updater which I never used; if I want to update a MOD I do it manually and each MOD at a time. I dont want MOD update notifications appearing in my game and extraneous data going over the internet no matter how minimal; that includes deleting all those miniavc files.

People who have played this game for a few years wanting continuous updates always seem to have problems with game crashes; this also doesnt account for Steam version versus KSP version which I dont even know if you can get KSP from their store anymore like I did years ago.

Following this method will help you identify a conflicting MOD.

I have also been getting a wierd GC HEAP problem maxing game memory out; very strange and I hardly havnt any MODS in; with the new Module Manager Madness we all seem to have to relearn the game setups !

Also if you are new I would highlyl suggest staying away from MODS for at least a month or more; play the stock game in it's various phases first. I work with MODS now and it takes me several weeks just to make a KSP game (the way I play it); I played KSP Stock for almost 3 months at version 18.5; the game is a little more difficult now even.

MODS are really what make this game for 'me'; many play it Stock only. Above all take this game slow; have fun and learn it first and MOD it later.

Commander Zeta
